Count data

As ecologists, we usually either measure things, or count things. When we measure things, they frequenly follow a more-or-less normal distribution (like the height of everyone in this room). However, when we count things (like the number of people collecting fish in the Delta every day) we end up with data that looks a lot different.

Count data differ from data with normal error in many ways, including

  1. counts are discrete, and can be zero or positive integers only,
  2. counts tend to bunch up on the small side of the range, creating a distribution with a positive skew,
  3. a sample of counts can have an abundance of zeros, and
  4. the variance of counts increases with the mean

Some count data can be approximated by a normal distribution and reasonably modeled with a linear model but more often, count data are modeled with Poisson distribution or negative binomial distribution using a generalized linear model (GLM). Poisson and negative binomial distributions are discrete probability distributions with two important properties:

  1. the distribution contains only zero and positive integers and
  2. the variance is a function of the mean.

This is count data - number of fish. Usually, we expect count data to follow a Poisson distribution. Poisson – A Poisson distribution is the probability distribution of the number of occurrences of some thing (in this case fish) generated by a process that generates the thing at a constant rate per unit effort (duration or space). This constant rate is λ, which is the expectation, so E(Y)= μ = λ. Because the rate per effort is constant, the variance of a Poisson variable equals the mean.

If we try to model catch of fish per trawl, we are going to get too many zeros (which is the second part of this lesson), so we are going to summarize the data and model total catch of Striped Bass per month.

SB = filter(FMWT, Species %in% c("Striped Bass age-0", "Striped Bass age-1",
                                 "Striped Bass age-1", "Striped Bass age-2")) %>%
              group_by(Year, SampleDate, SurveyNumber, StationCode, Volume, Yr_type) %>%
              summarize(Catch = sum(Catch, na.rm = T))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'Year', 'SampleDate', 'SurveyNumber',
## 'StationCode', 'Volume'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.
SBtot = group_by(SB, Year, SurveyNumber, Yr_type) %>%
  summarize(samples = n(), Volume = sum(Volume, na.rm = T), Catch = sum(Catch, na.rm = T))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'Year', 'SurveyNumber'. You can override
## using the `.groups` argument.

ggplot(SBtot, aes(x = Year, y = Catch, color = Yr_type))+ geom_point()

OK, we see there were a lot higher catches earlier in the time series, maybe higher catches in wet years, but it’s hard to tell.

Before we run a model, let’s look at a histogram of the data to see if it’s more or less normally distributed. Since it’s count data, it’s not likely to be, but you never know.

ggplot(SBtot, aes(x = Catch)) + geom_histogram()

Um, no.

hist(log(SBtot$Catch))

OK, log transforming gives us a pretty nice bell curve. Now we have two options:

  1. Do a regular old linear model on the log-transformed data.
  2. Do a generalized linear model on the raw data with a better distribution.

Let’s start with a log-transformed model

sblm = lm(log(Catch+1)~  Year + Yr_type, data = SBtot)

However, there are issues with transforming data. It works, and it allows you to use statistical tests that you learned in Stats 101, but tends to have greater error rates and poor predictive capabilities.

For an overview of the issues, I recommend this blog post and the article it was based on

https://www.r-bloggers.com/do-not-log-transform-count-data-bitches/

O’Hara, R. B., and D. J. Kotze. 2010. Do not log-transform count data. Methods in Ecology and Evolution 1(2):118-122. doi:https://doi.org/10.1111/j.2041-210X.2010.00021.x

Furthermore, using of transformed data or non-parametric hypothesis tests are are really justtools for computing “correct” p -values. They don’t give you parameter extimates that are very meaningful, making them hard to interpret.

Generalized Linear Models for Count Data

If you remember your introductory statistics classes, they probably said that count data are usually best described using a poisson distribution.

https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Poisson_distribution

While normal distributions are described by two parameters (mean and variance), Poisosn distributions are described by a single parameter (lambda) which is both the mean and variance, because in a Poisson distribution the mean is always equal to the variance.

If our striped bass data followed a poisson distribution, we would expect the (geometric) mean of the data to be equal to the variance.

#Geometric mean of striped bass data

(meanSB = exp(mean(log(SBtot$Catch+1))))
## [1] 138.4671
testSB = rpois(400, lambda = meanSB)
hist(testSB)

#variance
var(SBtot$Catch)
## [1] 1070614
mean(SBtot$Catch)
## [1] 462.305

So, we see that the variance is way higher than the mean.

We could also do a dispersion test, which relies on the fact that the Poisson distribution’s mean is equal to its variance, and the the ratio of the variance to the mean in a sample of n counts from a Poisson distribution should follow a Chi-square distribution with n-1 degrees of freedom.

dispersion_test <- function(x) 
{
  res <- 1-2 * abs((1 - pchisq((sum((x - mean(x))^2)/mean(x)), length(x) - 1))-0.5)

  cat("Dispersion test of count data:\n",
      length(x), " data points.\n",
      "Mean: ",mean(x),"\n",
      "Variance: ",var(x),"\n",
      "Probability of being drawn from Poisson distribution: ", 
      round(res, 3),"\n", sep = "")

  invisible(res)
}

dispersion_test(SBtot$Catch)
## Dispersion test of count data:
## 282 data points.
## Mean: 462.305
## Variance: 1070614
## Probability of being drawn from Poisson distribution: 0

So no. It is way over-dispersed. But just for fun, let’s look at what a linear model would look like.

We can use the DHARMa package to simulate residuals and create slightly different diagnostic plots, as well as check for overdispersison.

simOut <- simulateResiduals(fittedModel = lm2, n_sim = 200)
  plot(simOut, asFactor = F)

  testDispersion(simOut)

## 
##  DHARMa nonparametric dispersion test via sd of residuals fitted vs.
##  simulated
## 
## data:  simulationOutput
## dispersion = 1506.4, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: two.sided

You can see that the residuals versus fitted values plot has variance that increases as predicted values increase (that’s bad) and now the right tail of the normal QQ plot looks bad. Plus, there are lot of points outside teh cooks distance, which means they are outliers. And it’s WAY overdisspersed. This fits worse than than the log-transformed version!

So what now? We have two choices quasipoisson and negative binomial.

Quasipoisson

Quasipoisson’s are kinda weird, so check out this explanation from Zuur et al. 2009: A quassipoisson model uses the mean regression function and variance from the Poisson regression, but leaves the dispersion parameter unrestricted. (in a Poisson model dispersion = 1). Do not write in your report or paper that you used a quasi-Poisson distribution. Just say that you did a Poisson GLM, detected overdispersion, and corrected the standard errors using a quasi-GLM model where the variance is given by φ × μ, where μ is the mean and φ the dispersion parameter.

sb = glm(Catch~  Year, family = quasipoisson, data = SBtot) 
print("dispersion coefficient")
## [1] "dispersion coefficient"
summary(sb)$dispersion 
## [1] 575.7554
#test our residuals and QQ plot
res1 <- residuals(sb, type="deviance")
plot(log(predict(sb)), res1)

qqnorm(res1)

#test for differences between the two model specifications
print("p-value")
## [1] "p-value"
pchisq(summary(sb)$dispersion * lm2$df.residual, lm2$df.residual, lower = F)
## [1] 0
#it's very overdisperssed

So this looks better than the regular Poisson, but the right hand of the QQ plot is still a little off, and the Residuals versus Fitten plot isn’t great either.

Negative Binomial

We can try and see if a negative binomial model fits better than a quasipoisson. Negative binomial distributions account for overdisperssion, but variance is a quadratic function of the mean rather than a linear function of the mean (as in quasipoisson). There is lots of discussion as to which is better (e.g. Ver Hoef and Bveng 2007).

sbnb = glm.nb(Catch~  Year + Yr_type,  data = SBtot) 
summary(sbnb)

We can use the emmeans function for that.

The emmeans package reports the name of the term as the ratio of the coefficient term to the intercept term (the reference treatment level). Remember that a coefficient is a difference in conditional means, which gives us the relative effect of the one factor level versus another. Remember that effects on the response scale are not additive, but multiplicative!

Let’s look at this visually, first on the link scale:

library(visreg)

Now on the response scale:

visreg(sbnb, scale = "response")

Offests

So, you’ll notice that we modeled the counts of fish. However, it is much more common to want to know differences in catch per unit effort. With FMWT, the effort for each tow is pretty close, so it’s not a huge deal, but in other situations including effort is pretty important. Let’s try running a negative binomial model on CPUE!

SBtot$CPUE = SBtot$Catch/SBtot$Volume*10000
SBtot2 = dplyr::filter(SBtot, !is.na(Volume), Volume != 0)

Negative binomial models assume you have count data. If your data are not integers, you have two options:

  1. Round the data so they become integers. You shouldn’t do this. It’s wrong. Sometimes I do it in exploritory analyses if I only have CPUE data without the raw count data, but you should contact the data provider and get the raw count and effort data later.
  2. Use an offset. In this case, we take the log of volume (since there’s log-link).
sbnb3 = glm.nb(Catch ~ Year +offset(log(SBtot2$Volume)), data = SBtot2)

Zero-inflated model example

OK, that was striped bass. Striped bass are easy because we catch a lot of them. Also, I purposely used summaries by survey since we almost never have an entire month of FMWT (140 stations) with zero bass catch. However, frequently when we deal with count data we have more zeros than we should. This is (appropriately) known as zero-inflation.

Now let’s go back to our dataset, but instead of using Striped Bass, let’s pull the Delta Smelt data. We also aren’t going to summarize by survey, we are looking at each trawl as an independent data point. We are going to subset it to just data from before 2011, because we want a lot of zeros, but not THAT many zeros. We’ll just do 1990-2020, because I don’t want the dataset to be too big.

FMWT_DS = dplyr::filter(FMWT, Species == "Delta Smelt")


#just look at data from 1990-2020
FMWT_DS2 = dplyr::filter(FMWT_DS, Year <= 2020, Year > 1990, StationCode %in% c(605, 606, 608)) %>%
  mutate(Cond = scale(ConductivityTop), Sec = scale(Secchi), Year2 = scale(Year),
         Temp = scale(WaterTemperature))

What do we do about those extra zeros?

Too many Zeros

To deal with excess zeros, we can use a zero-inflated model, or a zero-augmented model (hurdle model) to figure out which to use, we need to understand the potential sources of zeros (modified from Zuur et al 2009):

  1. Structural zeros. Delta smelt are not caught because the habitat is not suitable (too hot, to clear, too salty).
  2. Design error. Delta smelt are not caught because the midwater trawl doesn’t sample the top part of hte water well and smelt hang out near the surface.
  3. Observer error. Delta smelt were caught, but Rosie thought they were Wakasagi.
  4. Smelt error. The habitat was suitable but the smelt weren’t using it.

Structural zeros and “smelt error” are considered “true zeros”, whereas design error and observer error are “false zeros”

Zero-augmented models (two-part models or hurdle models) do not differentiate between types of zeros. Zero-inflated models (mixture models) do differentiate so you can model zeros caused by the habitat being bad separately from the zeros caused by observer or design error.

Frequently, we can deal with data sets that have a lot of zeros just by using negative binomial models, or a few other tricks with our error terms. So, don’t jump right to the zero-inflated model UNLESS you have a clear conceptual model for why there might be different factors driving the ‘extra zeros’ than the counts.

In the case of the Delta Smelt, we know salinity, temperture, and turbidity are some of the major drivers of smelt presence and abundance. However, we know that smelt abundance has TANKED in recent years, and it isn’t really linked to changes in salinity, temperature, or turbidity at the local scale. Smelt often school, so when they are present, there are often several of them.

Therefore, we might want to try modeling the zeros seperate from abundance.

ZIP and ZINB

The overdisperssion in our Poisson model may have just been caused by the extra zeros, so a zero inflated Poisson might work (but like I said before, Poisson models almost never work so don’t waste your time). If there was also overdisspersion in the counts, then a zero inflated negative binomial will work better. Therefore, we will try both models and see which works better. To run these models we use the glmmTMB package

#try a zero-inflated Poisson
dszip = glmmTMB(Catch~  Cond + Sec + Temp + (1|StationCode), ziformula = ~ Year2,  family = "poisson", data = FMWT_DS2)
summary(dszip)

Note that the ziformula statement allows you to specify a different set of variables for the zero inflation part of it than the count part of it. So if you think that the counts are based on turbidity and salinity, but zeros are based on year. Using ~. means you use the same set of variables for both models. You can also include random effects, and we have added a station-level random effect to take into account the fact that samples from the same station are not independent. IF you’re not familiar with random effects, those will be covered this afternoon.

So, this ran nicely, but as I mentioned before, Poisson distributions are almost never appropriate for data in the real world, so we should check our diagnostic plots.

Hurdle Model

Hurdle models can’t model the different types of models differently, so I haven’t used them as often. But they may be useful for certain situations, especially if you have high confidence in your presence/absence data, or very complicated model structure that doesn’t work with the glmmTMB function.

Hurdle models basically have two steps. They first run a binomial model on presence/absence. Then they subset the data to include only the “presences” and run a generalized linear model on those presences. You can do this ‘by hand’ by subsetting your data and running two models, or you can use the glmmtmb function from with a truncated negative binomial distribution.

hurd = glmmTMB(Catch~ Cond +Sec + Temp + (1|StationCode), zi = ~ Year2,   
               family = "truncated_nbinom1", data = FMWT_DS2)

Bonus example: Not all data with zeros needs a zero-inflated model

I spent a lot of time getting confused, because I had a data set I wanted to use for an example that had a TON of zeros, but the negative binomial model fit better than a zero-inflated negative binomial model. Then I found this blog post. I’ll copy some of it here.

https://statisticalhorizons.com/zero-inflated-models/

In cases of overdispersion, the ZIP model typically fits better than a standard Poisson model. But there’s another model that allows for overdispersion, and that’s the standard negative binomial regression model. In all data sets that I’ve examined, the negative binomial model fits much better than a ZIP model, as evaluated by AIC or BIC statistics. And it’s a much simpler model to estimate and interpret. So if the choice is between ZIP and negative binomial, I’d almost always choose the latter.

But what about the zero-inflated negative binomial (ZINB) model? It’s certainly possible that a ZINB model could fit better than a conventional negative binomial model regression model. But the latter is a special case of the former, so it’s easy to do a likelihood ratio test to compare them (by taking twice the positive difference in the log-likelihoods).* In my experience, the difference in fit is usually trivial.

Of course, there are certainly situations where a zero-inflated model makes sense from the point of view of theory or common sense. For example, if the dependent variable is number of children ever born to a sample of 50-year-old women, it is reasonable to suppose that some women are biologically sterile. For these women, no variation on the predictor variables (whatever they might be) could change the expected number of children.

So next time you’re thinking about fitting a zero-inflated regression model, first consider whether a conventional negative binomial model might be good enough. Having a lot of zeros doesn’t necessarily mean that you need a zero-inflated model.
